{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01VSVUVQU41NAs2Kyqhe3CjQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me check the `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN` issue. The pattern includes `Í` (uppercase) and `í` (lowercase), but in the `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS` map, the keys are `\"¡\"` and `\"í\"` (lowercase). The pattern `/[0-9¡Íí€]/` includes `Í` (uppercase I-acute), but the substitution map doesn't have an entry for uppercase `Í`. Let me check if this matters...\n\nIn `repairOcrWord`, the function lowercases the word first (`const lower = word.toLowerCase()`), then checks `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS[lower[i]]`. \n\nSo `Í` would be lowercased to `í`, which IS in the map. The `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN` is used as an early-exit check on the original word, so having both cases in the regex is correct—it catches either form before the function lowercases and checks substitutions.\n\nThe pattern `/[0-9¡Íí€]/` will match digits 2, 3, 6, 7, 8, 9 even though they lack substitution entries in the map. When `repairOcrWord` processes a word like \"chicken3\", it triggers the pattern match, loops through characters, finds no substitution for \"3\", and returns the word unchanged since `positions.length` is 0. It's a minor inefficiency but not a bug—the early exit handles it gracefully.\n\nNow I'm noticing that `repairOcrText` gets called twice in the pipeline: once in `buildCandidates` before the hard filters, and again in `normalizeOcrTitle`. This means candidates that are already repaired will go through the repair logic a second time. Since `repairOcrWord` checks the artifact pattern, it might be doing redundant work on already-corrected text.\n\nLooking at the dedup protection logic, the compound title check with ` + `, ` : `, or ` & ` only shields the longer candidate from removal. But this could be overly broad—a simple title like \"Chips & Salsa\" would get protected even though it's not actually a compound title, just a regular title that happens to contain an ampersand.\n\nNow I'm noticing the `--\\s*\\w` pattern appears in two places: once in `METADATA_PATTERNS` (checked via `looksLikeMetadata`) and again directly in `passesHardFilters`. Since `passesHardFilters` calls `looksLikeMetadata`, the pattern gets evaluated twice through the same function, creating unnecessary redundancy. I'm noticing the explicit regex check in `passesHardFilters` duplicates what's already covered by the `looksLikeMetadata` function checking all the `METADATA_PATTERNS`, so that's redundant but not critical. I'm also spotting a style inconsistency where the code uses `string[]` notation in a few places like the positions object, when the style guide prefers `Array<T>` format instead. I'm seeing the Array notation issue extends throughout the internal functions too—the style guide applies to all code, not just exports. I should fix those `T[]` instances to use `Array<T>` instead. There are also a couple of minor redundancies I've spotted, like the `--` pattern appearing in both METADATA_PATTERNS and passesHardFilters, and the OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN matching digits that aren't in the substitution map. Now I'm looking back at the bilingual layout block to see if there are other issues worth addressing there.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2691,"cache_read_input_tokens":46428,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2691},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ec54b805-2592-4abe-8e4f-4011b51bb626","uuid":"5399d001-14f3-466f-a838-b6e099a805c2"}
