{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016vMXm965JDYqz841kU7bii","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have all the information needed for a thorough analysis. Here are the findings for each question:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Implementation Completeness — title-extractor.ts & food-dictionary.ts\n\n## Findings\n\n### 1. Is `repairOcrText` called in all the right places in `buildCandidates`?\n\nYes, coverage is complete across all three candidate generation paths:\n\n- **Single-line** (line 551): `repairOcrText(stripParentheticalGloss(stripPageNumber(line.text)))` — repair is applied to the stripped text before `passesHardFilters`.\n- **2-line join** (line 563): `repairOcrText(\\`${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text}\\`)` — repair applied to the raw join before hard-filter check.\n- **3-line join** (line 577): `repairOcrText(\\`${line.text} ${mergedLines[i + 1].text} ${mergedLines[i + 2].text}\\`)` — same treatment.\n- **Caps-coalescing inner loop** (line 490): `!isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text))` — repair is applied before the section-label check when deciding whether to extend a coalesced fragment.\n\nOne minor layering note: for the 2-line and 3-line joins, `repairOcrText` is applied to the raw (un-stripped) component lines, not to each component line after `stripPageNumber`/`stripParentheticalGloss`. This is inconsistent with the single-line path where stripping happens first. In practice this matters only if a page-number prefix contains a digit that happens to match a dictionary word after substitution (unlikely but possible).\n\nAdditionally, `repairOcrText` is called again inside `normalizeOcrTitle` (line 722), which runs on the final selected title. This provides a second pass for correctness, though it means repair runs twice for any candidate that both enters the pool and is ultimately selected.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Does the `isTitleAbsentPage` guard actually filter candidates effectively?\n\nThere is a structural ordering problem. The guard is applied **after** the fallback logic at line 1094–1104. The fallback runs first:\n\n```\nif (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n  const fallback = scored.slice().sort(...);\n  const rawScoreThreshold = fallback[0].position <= 2 ? -0.05 : 0.02;\n  if (fallback[0].rawScore > rawScoreThreshold) {\n    selected = [fallback[0]];\n  }\n}\n\n// Title-absent page guard runs here (line 1110)\nif (titleAbsent) {\n  selected = selected.filter(s => s.rawScore >= titleAbsentThreshold);  // 0.10\n  selected = selected.filter(s => s.position <= 2);\n}\n```\n\nThis ordering is correct in one case but problematic in another:\n\n- **Mushroom Risotto** case (body text, deep-file candidate at position 4): the fallback at line 1094 could populate `selected` with this candidate (it uses `-0.05` threshold for position ≤ 2, `0.02` for position > 2). If it sneaks in via the fallback, the `titleAbsent` guard's `position <= 2` filter will remove it. So for deep-file candidates this works.\n\n- **Sweet Potato Salad** case (picks up \"Salt and pepper\"): if \"Salt and pepper\" cleared the main threshold filter (line 1088) — which is plausible since it's a short non-ingredient phrase — it lands in `selected` before the `titleAbsent` check. Then `titleAbsent` applies `rawScore >= 0.10`. Whether this eliminates it depends on its raw embedding score. If it scored above 0.10 relative to the title reference embedding, the guard fails. The plan assumes this is below 0.10, but there is no explicit test to confirm that assumption is sound.\n\nMore generally: the guard does not apply to candidates that cleared the **main** threshold (line 1088), only to the result of `selected` at that late point. If a bad candidate already passed `threshold * 0.7`, it may also have `rawScore >= 0.10`. The guard would need to reject candidates that scored above the normal threshold on title-absent pages — but it doesn't do that. It only acts as a floor below 0.10, not as a ceiling or replacement threshold.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Does the bilingual layout boost at ~line 1050 actually fire when expected?\n\nThe logic has two silent failure modes:\n\n**First condition — `biSecond.origin === \"single\"`** (line 1050): `biSecond` must be a single-line candidate at position 1 or 2. If \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\" is a 2-line join candidate (i.e., the OCR split the line), it has `origin: \"2-line\"` and `biSecond` stays `undefined`. The block never fires.\n\n**Second condition — `sectionLabelNearby`** (line 1069–1071): the search window is `lines.slice(biFirst.position + 1, biFirst.position + 6)` — 5 raw source lines after `biFirst.position`. For the Golonka example, \"Ingredients:\" would need to appear within 5 raw lines of line 0. If there are blank lines or a subtitle line in between, \"Ingredients:\" might be at position 4 or 5 relative to line 0, which falls inside the window. But if there's a longer preamble or more blank lines, it misses.\n\n**Third condition — mixed-case check** (line 1061–1062):\n```typescript\nbiSecond.text !== biSecond.text.toUpperCase() &&\nbiSecond.text !== biSecond.text.toLowerCase()\n```\nA title like \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\" satisfies this. But a title like \"ROASTED PORK KNUCKLE\" (ALL_CAPS) does not — it's excluded by the `!== toUpperCase()` guard. The comment at line 1044 says the ALL_CAPS bilingual block above handles that case, so this is intentional but worth confirming the two blocks together cover all cases without gap.\n\nThe overall firing condition is: position-0 candidate with ≤2 words, position-1-or-2 single-line candidate with 2–5 words, mixed-case, not ingredient/instruction, and a section label within 5 raw lines of position 0. All five conditions must hold simultaneously. Any one failure silently prevents the boost.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Does the compound title dedup protection actually prevent the removal described in the plan?\n\nYes, the protection is in the right place and uses the correct logic. Line 1236:\n\n```typescript\nif (/ [+:&] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n```\n\nThis guards candidate `a` (the longer compound title) from being removed when a shorter candidate `b` is a substring of it. The regex matches ` + `, ` : `, and ` & ` with surrounding spaces — covering both plan examples (\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\" and \"PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\").\n\nOne divergence from the plan: the plan proposes `/ [+:] /` (two-character class) but the implementation uses `/ [+:&] /` (three-character class, adding `&`). This is strictly broader protection and consistent with other compound-title patterns in the codebase.\n\nOne edge case the guard does not cover: a compound title using ` / ` as a separator. But no plan example mentions that, and the existing 8-word exception at `passesHardFilters` already uses `/ [+:&/] /`, so a `/`-separated title would pass hard filters. Whether dedup could then wrongly discard it is not addressed by this guard.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Is the `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS` map complete for the cases mentioned in the plan?\n\nThere are two discrepancies:\n\n**`Í` (capital I-acute) is missing from `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS`.**\n\nThe plan explicitly lists `Í→i`. The map has `\"í\": [\"i\", \"l\"]` (lowercase í) but no `\"Í\"` key. The detection pattern `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN = /[0-9¡Íí€]/` does include `Í` (the pattern at line 641 contains it), so words containing `Í` will trigger `repairOcrWord`. However, when the loop at line 653 iterates through `lower[i]`, it lowercases the word first — so `Í` in the original becomes `í` in `lower`, and `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS[\"í\"]` does exist. This means the case issue is self-correcting through `.toLowerCase()`. The example from the plan (\"GRILÍED\" → \"GRILLED\") would work: `lower` = `\"grilíed\"`, position found for `í`, substitutions `[\"i\", \"l\"]` tried, `\"grilled\"` matches dictionary. So `Í` is effectively handled, just implicitly through lowercasing rather than an explicit key.\n\n**`2`, `3`, `6`, `7`, `8`, `9` are in `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN` but not in `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS`.**\n\n`OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN = /[0-9¡Íí€]/` matches all digits 0–9. But `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS` only defines `\"0\"`, `\"1\"`, `\"4\"`, `\"5\"`. Digits 2, 3, 6, 7, 8, 9 will cause `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(word)` to return `true` (bypassing the early return), but then the loop at line 653 finds no entry in `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS` for those digits. `positions` ends up empty, `positions.length === 0` triggers the early return at line 660, and the original word is returned unchanged.\n\nThis is not a correctness bug — it just means words containing those digits get a redundant pattern-test before returning unchanged. The plan only listed `1→i/l`, `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s`, `¡→i`, `Í→i` as the targeted substitutions, so 2/3/6/7/8/9 are intentionally unhandled. The pattern could be narrowed to `/[014501¡Íí€]/` for clarity, but the current form is functionally correct.\n\n**Summary of plan's listed substitutions vs. implementation:**\n\n| Plan item | In `OCR_SUBSTITUTIONS` | Handled correctly |\n|-----------|------------------------|-------------------|\n| `1→i`, `1→l` | `\"1\": [\"i\", \"l\"]` | Yes |\n| `0→o` | `\"0\": [\"o\"]` | Yes |\n| `4→a` | `\"4\": [\"a\"]` | Yes |\n| `5→s` | `\"5\": [\"s\"]` | Yes |\n| `¡→i` | `\"¡\": [\"i\"]` | Yes |\n| `Í→i` | Missing, but `\"í\": [\"i\", \"l\"]` covers it via `.toLowerCase()` | Yes, implicitly |\n\nAll plan-specified substitutions are covered. The `€→e` mapping (`\"€\": [\"e\"]`) is a bonus not mentioned in the plan and appears correct for that OCR artifact."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a18efa91bde57eaad (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 40367\ntool_uses: 12\nduration_ms: 94441</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ec54b805-2592-4abe-8e4f-4011b51bb626","uuid":"8dd338ee-cbb3-4656-bd93-77de5da8c234","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt